Ngram exploration¶

Looking at most frequent n-grams can give you a better understanding of the context in which the word was used.

In [31]:
def get_top_ngram(corpus, n=None):
    vec = CountVectorizer(ngram_range=(n, n)).fit(corpus)
    bag_of_words = vec.transform(corpus)
    sum_words = bag_of_words.sum(axis=0) 
    words_freq = [(word, sum_words[0, idx]) 
                  for word, idx in vec.vocabulary_.items()]
    words_freq =sorted(words_freq, key = lambda x: x[1], reverse=True)
    return words_freq[:10]

Topic modeling exploration with pyLDAvis¶

Topic modeling is the process of using unsupervised learning techniques to extract the main topics that occur in a collection of documents.

In [39]:
def preprocess_text(df):
    corpus=[]
    lem=WordNetLemmatizer()
    for textList in tqdm(YELP_sub.Token):      
        words=[lem.lemmatize(w) for w in textList]        
        corpus.append(words)
    return corpus

corpus=preprocess_text(YELP_sub)

dic=gensim.corpora.Dictionary(corpus)
bow_corpus = [dic.doc2bow(doc) for doc in corpus]

Latent Dirichlet Allocation (LDA) represents each document by the distribution of topics and each topic is represented by the distribution of words.

Wordcloud¶

Wordcloud is a great way to represent text data: the size and color of each word that appears in the wordcloud indicate its frequency or importance.

In [43]:
def show_wordcloud(data):
    wordcloud = WordCloud(
        background_color='white',
        stopwords=stopwords,
        max_words=100,
        max_font_size=30,
        scale=3,
        random_state=1)
   
    wordcloud=wordcloud.generate(str(data))

    fig = plt.figure(1, figsize=(12, 12))
    plt.axis('off')

    plt.imshow(wordcloud)
    plt.show()

# Here are some classifiers that support the `partial_fit` method
partial_fit_classifiers = {
    "SGD_svm": SGDClassifier(loss='hinge'),
    "SGD_log": SGDClassifier(loss='log'),
    "SGD_mHuber": SGDClassifier(loss='modified_huber'),
    "SGD_sHinge": SGDClassifier(loss='squared_hinge'),
    "Perceptron": Perceptron(),
    "NB Multinomial": MultinomialNB(alpha=0.01),
    "NB Complement": ComplementNB(alpha=0.01),
    "Passive-Aggressive": PassiveAggressiveClassifier(),
}

cls_stats = {}
for cls_name in partial_fit_classifiers:
    stats = {
        "n_train": 0,
        "accuracy": 0.0,
        "accuracy_history": [(0, 0)],
        "t0": time.time(),
        "runtime_history": [(0, 0)],
        "total_fit_time": 0.0,
    }
    cls_stats[cls_name] = stats
In [54]:
def progress(cls_name, stats):
    """Report progress information, return a string."""
    duration = time.time() - stats["t0"]
    s = "%20s classifier : \t" % cls_name
    s += "%(n_train)6d train docs " % stats
    s += "%(n_test)6d test docs " % test_stats
    s += "accuracy: %(accuracy).3f " % stats
    s += "in %.2fs (%5d docs/s)" % (duration, stats["n_train"] / duration)
    return s

total_vect_time = 0.0

In [56]:
for i, subSet in tqdm(enumerate(YELP_dicTrain.keys())):
    DF_tmp=YELP_dicTrain[subSet]

    X_train_text=list(DF_tmp.textToken)
    
    y_train=np.asarray(DF_tmp.stars, dtype=int)

    tick = time.time()
    X_train = vectorizer.transform(X_train_text)
    total_vect_time += time.time() - tick

    for cls_name, cls in partial_fit_classifiers.items():
        tick = time.time()
        # update estimator with examples in the current mini-batch
        cls.partial_fit(X_train, y_train, classes=all_classes)

        # accumulate test accuracy stats
        cls_stats[cls_name]["total_fit_time"] += time.time() - tick
        cls_stats[cls_name]["n_train"] += X_train.shape[0]
        tick = time.time()
        cls_stats[cls_name]["accuracy"] = cls.score(X_test, y_test)
        cls_stats[cls_name]["prediction_time"] = time.time() - tick
        acc_history = (cls_stats[cls_name]["accuracy"], cls_stats[cls_name]["n_train"])
        cls_stats[cls_name]["accuracy_history"].append(acc_history)
        run_history = (
            cls_stats[cls_name]["accuracy"],
            total_vect_time + cls_stats[cls_name]["total_fit_time"],
        )
        cls_stats[cls_name]["runtime_history"].append(run_history)
        
        Print=33
        if i % Print == 0:
            print(progress(cls_name, cls_stats[cls_name]))
        if i == len(YELP_dicTrain)-1:
            print(cls_name)
            predCls[cls_name]=cls.predict(X_val)
    if i % Print == 0:
        print("\n")

def plot_accuracy(x, y, x_legend):
    """Plot accuracy as a function of x."""
    x = np.array(x)
    y = np.array(y)
    plt.title("Classification accuracy as a function of %s" % x_legend)
    plt.xlabel("%s" % x_legend)
    plt.ylabel("Accuracy")
    plt.grid(True)
    plt.plot(x, y)

rcParams["legend.fontsize"] = 10
cls_names = list(sorted(cls_stats.keys()))

# Plot accuracy evolution
plt.figure()
for _, stats in sorted(cls_stats.items()):
    # Plot accuracy evolution with #examples
    accuracy, n_examples = zip(*stats["accuracy_history"])
    plot_accuracy(n_examples, accuracy, "training examples (#)")
    ax = plt.gca()
    ax.set_ylim((0.5, 0.7))
plt.legend(cls_names, loc="best")

plt.figure()
for _, stats in sorted(cls_stats.items()):
    # Plot accuracy evolution with runtime
    accuracy, runtime = zip(*stats["runtime_history"])
    plot_accuracy(runtime, accuracy, "runtime (s)")
    ax = plt.gca()
    ax.set_ylim((0.5, 0.7))
plt.legend(cls_names, loc="best")
